{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472198"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:55:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:55:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1129"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582857"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:58:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:58:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1129"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1129"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.58,0.21,0.1,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1129"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48916"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1129"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1129"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33916"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"564"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"2756"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8763"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42221"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44042"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48916"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA newborn girl is reviewed on the postnatal ward. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell with respiratory distress. Her pulse rate is 160/min, blood pressure 80/50 mmHg in the right arm and 60/40 mmHg in the right leg, respiratory rate 60/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The femoral pulses are weak bilaterally. Her feet are cold and cyanosed. Cardiorespiratory examination reveals no murmurs and clear lung fields.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following syndromes is most frequently associated with these examination findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sj\u00f6gren syndrome","Turner syndrome","Noonan syndrome","Williams syndrome","Klinefelter syndrome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis newborn girl presents with classical signs of coarctation of the aorta (CoA), including weak femoral pulses, cyanosed feet, low SpO2, and brachio-femoral delay (difference in blood pressure between upper and lower limbs). In congenital manifestations of this condition, there is a strong association with \u003Cstrong\u003ETurner syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. Approximately 5-15% of patients with CoA have Turner syndrome, and conversely, about 30% of patients with confirmed Turner syndrome have CoA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the other options have associated cardiac defects, none are as strongly associated with CoA as Turner syndrome:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESj\u00f6gren syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune disorder that primarily affects exocrine glands. In rare cases, it can be associated with complete heart block, but not typically with CoA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoonan syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with various congenital heart defects, most commonly pulmonary valve stenosis, but not typically CoA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWilliams syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by cardiovascular problems, particularly supravalvular aortic stenosis and renal artery stenosis, but not typically CoA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKlinefelter syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E may be associated with mitral valve prolapse in some cases, but not typically with CoA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the presentation of CoA in a newborn girl, Turner syndrome should be strongly suspected and further genetic testing may be warranted. Management would typically involve prostaglandin E1 infusion to maintain ductal patency, followed by surgical repair of the coarctation when the patient is stable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe following cardiovascular malformations are associated with each of the other syndromes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESj\u00f6gren syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E: complete heart block\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoonan syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E: pulmonary valve stenosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWilliams syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E: supravalvular aortic stenosis and renal artery stenosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKlinefelter syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E: mitral valve prolapse\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In a newborn with coarctation of the aorta, suspect concurrent Turner syndrome.","Coarctation of the aorta typically presents with weak femoral pulses, cyanosed feet, low oxygen saturations, and brachio-femoral delay."],"references":["Hijazi ZM. Clinical manifestations and diagnosis of coarctation of the aorta. In: Fulton DR, Armsby, C, editors. UpToDate. [Internet]. Waltham (MA): UpToDate Inc; 2022. [updated 2023 Feb; cited 2023 March 20]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis-of-coarctation-of-the-aorta?search=coarctation%20of%20aorta\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33916"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1129"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33916"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T14:20:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-19T14:20:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1129"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48916"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://ap